3","1365":"1365","about 1365":"about 1365","before 29 September 1374":"before 29 September 1374","Cubley, Uttoxeter, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Cubley, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Ecton, Northamptonshire, England":"Ecton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Montgomery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Sainte-Foy-de-Montgomery and Saint-Germain-de-Montgomery (Calvados). In Ireland this surname was present in the medieval period, died out, and was then reintroduced from Scotland in the 17th century. It has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>Mac Iomaire</b> and in Scotland as <b>Mac Gumaraid</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Montgomery Lord of Cubley was born in 1356, in Derbyshire, England, his father, Walter Montgomery, was 42 and his mother, Matilda Furnival, was 33. He married Margaret Foljambe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1424, in his hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1356–1424":"1356–1424","1365–1453":"1365–1453","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1365–1374":"1365–1374","1380–1456":"1380–1456","1380–1465":"1380–1465","1314–1374":"1314–1374","1323–1385":"1323–1385","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1385":"1385","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1338":"1338","1424":"1424","1314":"1314","1456":"1456","1356":"1356","1323":"1323","September 1374":"september 1374","1465":"1465","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1365":"umbes 1365","before 29 September 1374":"enne 29. septembrit 1374","Cubley, Uttoxeter, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Cubley, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Ecton, Northamptonshire, England":"Ecton, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1356–1424":"1356–1424","1365–1453":"1365–1453","1338–Female":"1338–Kuollut","1365–1374":"1365–1374","1380–1456":"1380–1456","1380–1465":"1380–1465","1314–1374":"1314–1374","1323–1385":"1323–1385","about 1380":"noin 1380","1385":"1385","1374"